<TITLE>Tribune Opinion: Salida del Sol Academy put our children in danger by investigating sex-related compliant without calling police</TITLE>


<TEXT>
Greeleys police department is <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">investigating</EVENT> whether officials at Salida del Sol Academy <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">broke</EVENT> the law by <EVENT eid="e3" class="I_ACTION">failing</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e4" class="REPORTING">report</EVENT> a sex-related complaint involving an eighth-grade girl and a male teacher. 
 
We dont <EVENT eid="e5" class="I_STATE">need</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">wait</EVENT> for the investigation to <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">wonder</EVENT> what the heck Executive Director Joe Melendez and school security guard Anthony Antuna were <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">thinking</EVENT>. 
 
Melendez and Antuna and apparently members of the school board did one of the worst things school leaders can <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">do</EVENT> by <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">doing</EVENT> their own investigation instead of <EVENT eid="e11" class="REPORTING">reporting</EVENT> it to the police: They <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">put</EVENT> their schools interests before the safety of our children. 
 
You probably <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">saw</EVENT> the movie Spotlight, <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">right</EVENT>? It won an Oscar for Best Picture. Anyway, the movie was about the brilliant work the Boston Globe did to <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">uncover</EVENT> the damage <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">wrought</EVENT> by Catholic Church leaders who <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">covered</EVENT> up sexual abuse among the priesthood. As a result, many more kids were <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">abused</EVENT>. 
 
Mandatory reporting laws exist precisely so something like that doesnt happen again. Thats why it doesnt matter that Melendez and Antuna are former police officers. When they <EVENT eid="e19" class="I_ACTION">chose</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e20" class="I_ACTION">investigate</EVENT> the complaint themselves, they <EVENT eid="e21" class="I_ACTION">showed</EVENT> they <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">learned</EVENT> nothing from Spotlight or any other incident like it. We dont know what <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">happened</EVENT> between the teacher and the girl. But we arent <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">soothed</EVENT> by the fact that Melendez and Antuna <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">fired</EVENT> the teacher. In our mind, this <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">makes</EVENT> the oversight worse. This means they <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">released</EVENT> a man they <EVENT eid="e28" class="I_ACTION">deemed</EVENT> unfit to <EVENT eid="e29" class="OCCURRENCE">work</EVENT> at their school out into the world to <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">save</EVENT> the school some perceived embarrassment. 
 
In fact, some evidence <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">shows</EVENT> the teacher <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">displaying</EVENT> a disturbing pattern of inappropriate behavior and possibly abuse. He was apparently <EVENT eid="e33" class="OCCURRENCE">coached</EVENT> on how to <EVENT eid="e34" class="OCCURRENCE">conduct</EVENT> himself appropriately and professionally in order to <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">make</EVENT> sure there <EVENT eid="e36" class="OCCURRENCE">werent</EVENT> any allegations, a board member, Virginia Rosales, <EVENT eid="e37" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> an in email. 
 
We certainly would have <EVENT eid="e38" class="REPORTING">reported</EVENT> it if there was something sufficient enough to <EVENT eid="e39" class="OCCURRENCE">do</EVENT> that, Rosales <EVENT eid="e40" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> in the email. 
 
The thing is, thats not Salidas decision to <EVENT eid="e41" class="OCCURRENCE">make</EVENT>, and thats not the <EVENT eid="e42" class="OCCURRENCE">decision</EVENT> of Melendez and Antuna. Thats for law enforcement to <EVENT eid="e43" class="OCCURRENCE">decide</EVENT>. That is, in fact, what law enforcement will <EVENT eid="e44" class="OCCURRENCE">decide</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">now</TIMEX3>. Only <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">now</TIMEX3>, in our mind, its mostly too late. A man who potentially did something inappropriate to an eighth-grader, and who may have <EVENT eid="e45" class="OCCURRENCE">shown</EVENT> a pattern of abuse to children, is out there <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">now</TIMEX3>, and its entirely possible he could be <EVENT eid="e46" class="OCCURRENCE">teaching</EVENT> again, or <EVENT eid="e47" class="OCCURRENCE">working</EVENT> with children in some way. Our children are now not as safe as they could be as a result. 
 
We <EVENT eid="e48" class="STATE">say</EVENT> its mostly too late. Theres still one outcome we hope <EVENT eid="e49" class="OCCURRENCE">happens</EVENT> soon. It would be inappropriate for us to <EVENT eid="e50" class="OCCURRENCE">root</EVENT> for criminal charges, but we at least <EVENT eid="e51" class="OCCURRENCE">look</EVENT> forward to the police department <EVENT eid="e52" class="OCCURRENCE">completing</EVENT> a fair, accurate and scouring investigation of the school board, Melendez and Antuna. Most of all, we <EVENT eid="e53" class="I_STATE">want</EVENT> it to be as public as possible. Thats exactly the kind of embarrassment they <EVENT eid="e54" class="I_STATE">wanted</EVENT> the school to <EVENT eid="e55" class="OCCURRENCE">avoid</EVENT>. The only difference <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">now</TIMEX3> is that theyre the ones who <EVENT eid="e56" class="OCCURRENCE">caused</EVENT> it. 
 
 
 The Tribune Editorial Board
</TEXT>


